>inspiration from existing media sources
First off, Farscape. There was a lot of unhinged, off-the-rails shit in just about every episode, a lot of which can be adapted to /hmofa/.

Along that theme, a general thing to do is watch & read a lot of sci fi. Almost all of it (especially Start Trek, I'm looking at you) introduces some very interesting themes and concepts, then fails to develop & deliver on them. It's a huge hobby among the Trek community to pick apart all sorts of Trek sci fi & tech & other sociopolitcal commentary and rant and rave and rewrite all the shit that got retard-tier treatment or was introduced as eye candy and then forgotten.

Read David Brin's Uplift books. Read C. J. Cherryh's Chanur saga. Rewatch The Fifth Element. Watch Immortal, if you haven't already. Have you seen Dark City? Find a copy of the director's cut, throw some anthro into it and you have a nearly unique setting to explore. Dune, for fuck's sake. Dune, movies & books, almost anything Frank Herbert. Vast potential to explore hundreds of themes with just Frank Herbert. He's not just a meme, he was the Real Thing, just a genius of ideas. Larry Niven for head candy & humorous takes on many tropes. One of the classic sci fi writers (and fantasy), Andre Norton. Over a hundred fairly short novels, she was was obsessed with human & animal partnerships, uplifted species almost before David Brin was born.

https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/AndreNorton

Find a copy of Star Man's Son, 2250 A.D. (alt title Daybreak 2250 AD). You. Just. Know. Beast Master. Breed to Come.

> tl;dr - Yes. All sci fi stories/movies have thousands of examples for inspiration. That's what sci fi is and does.

Farscape is great, and massively underrated. It was pretty ahead of its time, but I don't think it'd fly at all today. It was a weird partial deconstruction of existing science fiction at its time, and I don't think most viewers ever really got into it. And I guess a lot of them were weirded out by the muppets. Took some getting used to.

However, I think that's a really bad take on Star Trek. We're talking about a show that has existed since the 60's and undeniably influenced both the genre of science fiction and real life greatly. It has existed for a long time, it has a lot of content, and it has had a shitload of people working on it. You can't really expected everyone involved to have the sort of autistic attention to detail that an established fanbase is going to have, especially when it might get in the way of actually telling the story you want to tell. And all of the shit the community comes up with is head canon. None of it is real. I mean, take that episode where Picard and co turn into children. It's a good example of what you're talking about. On the face of it it's kinda retarded to not take the extra years of life afforded by it (especially if you're Picard), or that the Federation doesn't end up with a functionally immortal population that steps into the transporter to rejuvenate every few decades. But the episode wasn't about that. It was about two stodgy characters turning into kids and having to deal with it. Picard hates kids. And for how easy it is to take the absence of a few lines about it being non-repeatable and imagining the Federation is retarded for not following up, it's even easier to imagine that it can't be repeated and staying in that state will end up giving you supercancer down the line.

I hate the idea of a setting having to be caulked shut at every point to prevent autists from running with every issue that was never the point in the first place. I'll take flawed but imaginative over sensible but stunted any day.
